<seg id=1> Journalist Reported On Rape Of Chinese Woman During May Riots, Questioned By Indonesian Police </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AGENCE FRANCE PRESSE WIRE Jakarta) The Committee to Protect Journalists, an international organization defending the freedom of the press, expressed alarm at the Indonesian police for questioning a journalist who reported on the rape of a Chinese businesswoman during the riots in May. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The committee, headquartered in New York, said that Gu Nawan, a reporter working for the magazine Jakarta-Jakarta, was taken to police headquarters and interrogated on Thursday. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The committee said that Gu Nawan's July report quoted a woman who was raped. </seg>
<seg id=5> The New York Times interviewed the same victim in a story published on July 10. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In a letter to Indonesian President BJ Habibie, the committee said that the summons issued by police was "the first step by the police in bringing up charges." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The committee "is very concerned that using the law in this way will have a negative effect upon freedom of speech." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The committee was referring to Muslim organizations pressuring the government to arrest Gu Nawan under Article 156 of the criminal code. </seg>
<seg id=9> The article forbids people from defaming religious groups. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The International League of Independent Journalists also protested the questioning of Gu Nawan. </seg>
<seg id=11> It said, this will "set a precedent, weakening the greater freedom of the press gained after former President Suharto left office." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> The Committee to Protect Journalists urged Habibie to "stop opposing Gu Nawan", and demanded that both sides settle the dispute in the civil courts. </seg>
<seg id=13> It also appealed for both sides to "make every effort to get rid of the defamation article in the criminal code." </seg>
</p>
